<p style="text-align:justify;">which answers the purpose of soap<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">This Village formerly consisted of nine hundred but the small pox and other misfortunes have re<span class="AddHand-editors">[du]</span>ced them to the present small number.  They however have been settled upon this spot time out of mind<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  These Indians are not so fond of cultivating the ground as their neighbours<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  They do not stable their horses in the same huts with themselves but have small enclosures unter the stages which front their <span class="AddHand-author">huts</span> for that purpose.  Their canoes have one end square and the other round and make use of in the same manner as those of the Mandanes.  They bring water in Buffaloe <span class="AddHand-author"><span style="text-decoration:underline;">paunches</span></span> from Knife river which is at some distance for common use<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  They reside at this Village only during <span class="AddHand-author">the</span> summer season.  Early in the fall they go for the snake lodge wher<span class="AddHand-author">e</span> they reside for the winter in huts similar to these mentioned<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  But here they do not remain inactive: All, excepting the old people form into large parties and make long hunting excursions to the westward<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Early in the spring they return to these Villages to sow their fields to gather the drift wood and secure the drowned Buffaloes which come down with the ice<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
